\begin{definition}
A general linear method $(A, U, B, V)$ is `stable' if there exists a constant $C$ such that, for all $n = 1, 2, \dots$, $\|V^n\| \leq C$.
\end{definition}

context_latex:
\paragraph{Context}
General linear methods are defined by matrices $(A,U,B,V)$.
Preconsistency requires a vector $u$ satisfying
\begin{equation}
V u = u, \qquad U u = 1.
\end{equation}
Consistency requires a vector $v$ such that
\begin{equation}
B\mathbf{1} + V v = u + v.
\end{equation}
Stability is defined by the power-boundedness of $V$.
